4. Proposed Approach: Architecture & Design

The proposed system is a software layer residing between the device’s modem, sensors, and the Tesla ecosystem. It consists of four integrated modules.

4.1 Connectivity Management Layer

Predictive Handoff Engine

· Model: Lightweight LSTM (Long Short‑Term Memory) with inputs: GPS, vehicle motion data, historical signal strength, and upcoming terrain (via offline maps). The model runs on the Qualcomm X80’s dedicated tensor accelerator, avoiding main CPU wake‑ups.
· Output: Predicted best network (Starlink Mobile, 5G, Wi‑Fi) 30 seconds ahead. The engine pre‑configures the modem to reduce scanning and TTFF.

Doppler‑Aware Scheduling

· Starlink LEO satellites move at ~7.5 km/s, causing significant Doppler shifts. The AI layer uses Tesla’s high‑precision GNSS (Global Navigation Satellite System) and vehicle velocity data to calculate the expected frequency offset before the phone’s modem attempts a handshake, reducing TTFF by an estimated 70%.

Vehicle‑as‑Relay (VaR) Cooperative MIMO

· When the phone is in or near a Tesla, it transitions from standalone satellite mode to cooperative MIMO:
  · The car’s roof‑mounted Starlink antenna (or its own cellular modem) handles the physical layer (L1).
  · The phone maintains the session layer, with data tunnelled over Wi‑Fi 6/7.
  · This reduces the phone’s transmit power (P<sub>tx</sub>) to near‑zero.

4.2 Energy Management Layer

AI Power Budget Orchestrator

· Monitors real‑time power draw of screen, CPU, modem, and satellite transceiver. Dynamically allocates budget based on user context (driving, stationary, indoors) and predicted access to charging (vehicle, Powerwall, solar).
· Uses a context‑aware power model trained on Tesla vehicle data (e.g., whether the car is plugged in).

Bidirectional Energy Protocol

· Leverages Tesla Powershare APIs and Qi wireless charging coils.
  · Receive: Phone charges from vehicle (up to 15W wireless) when inside or parked.
  · Supply: Phone reverse‑charges low‑power accessories (key fob, watch) using reverse wireless charging.
  · Scheduling: Charging is coordinated with solar production data from Powerwall, maximizing renewable self‑consumption.

4.3 Ecosystem Integration Layer

· Unified Dashboard: Single UI for vehicle state, Powerwall, Solar Roof, and phone battery. AI suggests optimal charging times to maximize solar self‑consumption.
· Universal Key: UWB passive entry for vehicles, with fallback to Starlink‑based remote commands when out of Bluetooth range.

4.4 Security & Privacy Layer

· Satellite‑Relayed Secure Transactions: Zero‑trust messaging protocol over Starlink for authorising payments (e.g., Supercharger sessions) without relying on terrestrial internet.
· On‑Device AI: All personal data stays on device; only aggregated diagnostics optionally shared.

4.5 Hardware Abstraction

· The system is designed to run on any Starlink Mobile‑compatible device with a Qualcomm X80 (or newer) modem and Android 16 (V‑Release) satellite stack.
· Prototyping uses a Samsung Galaxy S25 T‑Satellite edition modified with custom firmware (AOSP‑based).

