5. Technical Deep Dive: Proactive Vehicle‑as‑Relay (P‑VaR) Protocol

To ensure seamless handoff—where a VoIP call or data stream doesn’t drop as the user enters or exits a Tesla—the protocol moves from reactive switching to proactive session migration.

5.1 UWB‑Gated Handoff Logic

The transition follows a three‑step synchronization process:

1. Proximity Awareness (Handshake) – As the user approaches within 5–10 m, the phone and vehicle establish a secure UWB link. The phone’s AI layer requests the vehicle’s current Starlink/LTE signal status.
2. Tunneling (Warm Start) – Before shutting down its own satellite modem, the phone establishes a Multipath TCP (MPTCP) tunnel over the vehicle’s local Wi‑Fi 6/7.
3. Physical Layer Cut‑over – Once the tunnel is verified, the phone puts its internal satellite transceiver into deep sleep, offloading all transmit power to the car.

5.2 Session Anchor & Virtual MAC

· A lightweight session anchor runs on the Tesla Infotainment System (MCU‑Z) to maintain the connection state with the Starlink ground station.
· The phone presents a virtual MAC address to the vehicle, allowing the car to “spoof” the phone’s identity to the satellite network. This prevents re‑authentication delays (typically 5–10 s) and ensures session continuity.

5.3 Exit Scenario: Predictive Wake‑up

When the car is put in Park or the door handle is touched:

· The phone’s AI pre‑warms the internal satellite modem using Doppler pre‑compensation from the vehicle’s last known orbital ephemeris data.
· The phone knows exactly where to point its beam, eliminating the “search” phase and reducing TTFF to under 2 s.

5.4 Mathematical Energy Gain

The energy benefit is quantified using the Relay Gain Ratio:

G_r = \frac{P_{\text{modem,standalone}}}{P_{\text{local link}} + P_{\text{overhead}}}

where P_{\text{modem,standalone}} is the phone’s satellite transmit power, P_{\text{local link}} is the Wi‑Fi/UWB power, and P_{\text{overhead}} includes the car’s relay processing. In early simulations, G_r > 4.5, meaning the phone’s battery lasts over four times longer during active data transfer when using the vehicle as a relay.

