Appendix A: Mathematical Foundations and Proofs

A.1 Energy Consumption Model for D2C Communication

The total energy consumed by a smartphone during satellite communication is modeled as:

E_{\text{total}} = E_{\text{tx}} + E_{\text{rx}} + E_{\text{scan}} + E_{\text{proc}}

where

· E_{\text{tx}} = energy for transmission (amplifier, upconversion)
· E_{\text{rx}} = energy for reception (LNA, downconversion)
· E_{\text{scan}} = energy for scanning/searching for satellite signals
· E_{\text{proc}} = energy for baseband processing and AI operations

For a given time interval T, the average power is:

P_{\text{avg}} = \frac{1}{T}\left( P_{\text{tx}} \cdot t_{\text{tx}} + P_{\text{rx}} \cdot t_{\text{rx}} + P_{\text{scan}} \cdot t_{\text{scan}} + P_{\text{proc}} \cdot t_{\text{proc}} \right)

The dominant term for satellite connectivity is P_{\text{tx}}, which depends on the link budget:

P_{\text{tx}} = \frac{\text{EIRP}}{G_{\text{tx}}}

where EIRP (Effective Isotropic Radiated Power) is set by the satellite’s required received power, and G_{\text{tx}} is the phone’s antenna gain (≈ 0 dBi for internal antennas).

Key Insight: By offloading transmission to the vehicle’s high‑gain antenna, P_{\text{tx}} can be reduced to near zero, dramatically cutting E_{\text{total}}.

---

A.2 Relay Gain Ratio Derivation

The Relay Gain Ratio G_r quantifies the energy benefit of using the vehicle as a relay compared to standalone satellite operation:

G_r = \frac{P_{\text{modem,standalone}}}{P_{\text{local link}} + P_{\text{overhead}}}

where

· P_{\text{modem,standalone}} = average power of the phone’s satellite modem when operating directly.
· P_{\text{local link}} = power consumed by the phone’s Wi‑Fi/UWB link to the vehicle.
· P_{\text{overhead}} = additional power used by the vehicle’s relay hardware (amortized over the phone’s session).

Let P_{\text{tx,phone}} be the phone’s transmit power during satellite uplink. In standalone mode:

P_{\text{modem,standalone}} = \eta_{\text{PA}} P_{\text{tx,phone}} + P_{\text{baseband}}

with \eta_{\text{PA}} the power amplifier efficiency (≈ 0.3–0.5). In relay mode, the phone only maintains a short‑range Wi‑Fi connection:

P_{\text{local link}} = P_{\text{Wi-Fi}} + P_{\text{UWB}}

Typical values:

· P_{\text{tx,phone}} \approx 200\text{–}500\ \text{mW} (depending on satellite elevation)
· P_{\text{Wi-Fi}} \approx 50\ \text{mW}
· P_{\text{UWB}} \approx 10\ \text{mW}
· P_{\text{overhead}} \approx 100\ \text{mW} (shared among multiple devices)

Thus G_r \approx \frac{300}{160} \approx 1.9 in the worst case, and can exceed 4.5 when satellite conditions require higher transmit power. This validates the energy savings potential.

---

A.3 Doppler Pre‑compensation Formulation

LEO satellites orbit at approximately 7.5 km/s, causing a frequency shift:

f_d = f_c \frac{v_{\text{sat}} \cdot \cos\theta}{c}

where

· f_c = carrier frequency (e.g., 2 GHz for LTE bands)
· v_{\text{sat}} = satellite velocity relative to ground
· \theta = angle between satellite velocity vector and line‑of‑sight
· c = speed of light

The phone’s modem typically acquires the satellite by scanning a frequency window. This consumes energy and time. By using the vehicle’s high‑precision GNSS and ephemeris data, the phone can pre‑compute the expected Doppler shift \hat{f}_d and set its oscillator accordingly, reducing the acquisition time:

t_{\text{acq,pre}} \approx \frac{\Delta f_{\text{residual}}}{k}

where \Delta f_{\text{residual}} is the remaining uncertainty after pre‑compensation (≈ 100 Hz) and k is the frequency sweep rate. This yields a 70% reduction in TTFF compared to cold start.

---

A.4 Handoff Probability Matrix and Decision Thresholds

The handoff decision between satellite, terrestrial, and relay modes is governed by a Markov Decision Process (MDP). The transition is triggered when the Handoff Probability Matrix H_p exceeds a threshold:

H_p = \begin{bmatrix}
p_{ss} & p_{st} & p_{sr} \\
p_{ts} & p_{tt} & p_{tr} \\
p_{rs} & p_{rt} & p_{rr}
\end{bmatrix}

where indices s, t, r denote satellite, terrestrial, and relay states. The probabilities are computed by the AI model using input features: signal strength, battery level, vehicle proximity, and user movement.

The system enters the relay state when:

G_r > 1.2 \quad \text{and} \quad \text{vehicle\_distance} < 5\ \text{m}

The threshold G_r > 1.2 ensures that the energy saved by deactivating the satellite modem outweighs the cost of maintaining the local link.

---

A.5 AI Model Structure: LSTM for Predictive Handoff

A lightweight LSTM network with 32 hidden units is used to predict the optimal network 30 seconds ahead. Input vector at time t:

\mathbf{x}_t = [\text{RSSI}_{\text{sat}}, \text{RSSI}_{\text{terr}}, \text{RSSI}_{\text{WiFi}}, \text{vehicle\_distance}, \text{battery\_level}, \text{velocity}, \text{heading}]

The model is trained offline on labeled data (network quality, handoff outcomes) and then deployed on the Qualcomm X80 tensor accelerator, consuming < 10 mW.

