Appendix B: System Architecture and Protocol Specifications

B.1 High-Level System Architecture

The system is composed of three main entities:

· Smartphone (running custom firmware)
· Tesla Vehicle (running a relay agent on the infotainment system)
· Starlink Satellite Network (D2C infrastructure)

The smartphone’s software stack is divided into:

· Application Layer: Unified dashboard, user interaction.
· AI Optimization Layer: Handoff prediction, Doppler pre‑compensation, power budgeting.
· Connectivity Layer: Modem control, P‑VaR protocol, session management.
· Energy Layer: Power monitoring, wireless charging, Powershare integration.
· Security Layer: Encrypted messaging, zero‑trust transactions.

The vehicle runs a lightweight Relay Agent that:

· Exposes a virtual network interface for the phone.
· Maintains a session anchor with Starlink.
· Manages local Wi‑Fi/UWB communication.
· Exposes Powershare APIs for energy transfer.

B.2 Proactive Vehicle‑as‑Relay (P‑VaR) Protocol Detail

P‑VaR operates in three phases:

1. Proximity Detection (UWB):
   · UWB ranging at 1 m accuracy, range 0–10 m.
   · When distance < 10 m, the phone initiates a secure handshake (Diffie‑Hellman over UWB).
2. Warm‑Start Tunnel Establishment:
   · Phone establishes an MPTCP (Multipath TCP) connection over Wi‑Fi 6 (802.11ax) to the vehicle’s relay agent.
   · The relay agent requests a session anchor from the Starlink ground station, providing the phone’s virtual MAC.
3. Session Migration:
   · Once the tunnel is active and the phone is inside the vehicle (distance < 2 m or door open), the phone deactivates its satellite transceiver.
   · The vehicle’s high‑gain antenna takes over the physical layer. Data packets are forwarded via the MPTCP tunnel.

Exit Procedure (phone leaving vehicle):

· Vehicle detects door open or seat unoccupied via CAN bus.
· The vehicle pushes current satellite ephemeris and Doppler shift to the phone via UWB/Wi‑Fi.
· The phone pre‑warms its modem and sets the oscillator to the pre‑computed frequency.
· The phone re‑acquires the satellite in < 2 s and notifies the vehicle to terminate the relay.

B.3 Session Anchor and Virtual MAC Mechanism

To avoid re‑authentication delays (which can take 5–10 s on current D2C networks), the vehicle’s relay agent spoofs the phone’s identity:

· The phone provides its IMEI/IMSI to the vehicle over a secure channel.
· The vehicle presents this identity to the Starlink core network, establishing a session anchor.
· The anchor maintains the PDP (Packet Data Protocol) context for the phone.
· When the phone later reconnects directly, it can resume the same session without re‑authentication.

